author: @TimJohnson-x1o
comment: When American brands give their quoted specs like 0-60 times there is an asterisk* caveat. In America everything comes with fine print, you always have to read the fine print. The caveat is that they used race fuel, drag slicks, a prepped surface and a pro driver on a perfect day, going slightly downhill, and did several runs before the car overheated/falls apart, then they quoted you the best time they got and still rounded down.  When a German brand like Porsche gives you the quoted time it's a bare minimum the car will do with any driver in any conditions on any road any day at any time, over and over and over again. Those that know, know. Those that haven't figured it out by now, with all the information available online these days are just hopeless and or delusional.

author: @amg863
comment:
Lamborghini is more of a head turner. Probably makes you feel more special when you drive it because it's so exotic and uncompromising. 

The Porsche is the more reasonable choice. It is more reliable, more understated, more refined and practical. It really depends on your priorities. If you already have a track car or a fun daily, maybe what you want is a flashy lambo to spice things up on the weekend. For me the appeal of the Porsche is you can drive it everyday and blend in everywhere. You don't have to worry too much about it
